                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="verdana" size="2" color="white"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> <blockquote id="quote"><font size="1" face="trebuchet ms,tahoma" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><i>Originally posted by Rekcim</i><br /><br />What pisses me off about the whole thing is SoEs failure to even TRY to stop this shit.   They don't care about some guy pharming PP to sell, but they will come to your house swat style if you exploit some easy exp somewhere.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></font id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"><br /><br />I <i>halfway</i> agree with you on this point.  What's truly outrageous is that, as you said, if you exploit for experience they (SOE) hit the roof.  There's emergency patches (and the downtime that comes with them), acount-banning "witchunts" whereby Guides and GM's will spend time (that <i>could</i> be spent answering the eternal backlog of petitions) hanging out in exploitable areas hoping to "bust" people, etc.  These morons have their priorities backwards.  How fast can a <i>mediocre</i> guild PL a noob to 65 <i>anyway</i>? A few stinkin' days if they really want to.  Now, how fast can that same guild amass 50+ million plat?  Get the point, SOE?  <br /><br />Given the speed and ease with which one can hit 65 these days <i>anyway</i> ("with a little help from their friends"), the "damage" to the "balance of the game" that XP exploits cause PALES in comparison to the very noticable and unbalancing damage that's done by the UNGODLY inflation brought about by these massive plat exploits, which they (SOE) allowed to continue for several fookin months (upwards of 6 months for the last one, I believe).  It almost makes me wonder if certain GM's and/or people on the dev team didn't have a financial stake in Yantis.  There were a handful of very specific locations one's toon had to be in for the "big" macroing plat exploits to work.  Six months to find the problem and the offenders?  Bullshit, they could have done it in 1 night.<br /><br />Where I disagree with your above sentiment is that I don't think there's anything "wrong" with people <b>farming</b> plat to sell.  While some people think that using the wording that they're actually selling their "time" as opposed to the "plat" is just a clever workaround of SOE policies, it's actually the truth.  It is the time involved in amassing vast quantities of plat that makes (made, anyway) plat "scarce" and hence valuable.  It's just how the world works.<br /><br />As I see it, selling <b>(farmed)</b> "plat" is ethically no different than selling your services at a "real job," you're trading your valuable time and "labor" to someone who recognizes the value in it and is willing to pay for it.  Does it suck that some people can't afford to buy plat, and thus have to earn it the old-fashioned way?  Sure; it also sucks that some of us had to buy our own first vehicles, while some of our classmates got a brand-new hotrod from their daddy for their 16th birthday.  It's no different.  Again, it's just how the world works.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="1" face="trebuchet ms,tahoma" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><br />Its a joke, they might as well say they don't care about selling pp/items and just let everyone sell shit.  This way yantis would have too much competition and his shit would be worthless.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></font id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"><br /><br />Yes, they should. IMHO, if SOE were smart there would have always been an in-game "auction" setup for people to sell plat/items/whatever for RL cash, with the stipulation that SOE gets a percentage of the sale price.  They would have made a lot of money, been able to excercise some control over the plat market, <i>and</i> would have prevented the creation of a "black market" dominated (as black markets always are) by unscrupulous people like Yantis.  Surely they foresaw that there would be a market for plat.  Even grade-schoolers have heard of "supply and demand."  <i>Again,</i> it's how the world works.  We don't stop being human beings just because we're playing a game.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="1" face="trebuchet ms,tahoma" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><br />I feel sorry for the dumb mofos that buy this crap.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></font id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"><br /><br />I feel sorry for the dumb mofos that buy all sorts of tangible goods, but it's their money to spend.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="1" face="trebuchet ms,tahoma" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><br />I  can almost agree that selling an account should be ok, because you shelled out $$ for all the disks etc..  Better someone enjoys your account then have 3-4 yrs go down the tubes.  Selling pp/items is a bit different, because they pharm/exploit EQ and introduce way more pp/items then would normally be seen.<br /><hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></font id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"><br /><br />Unfortunately, inflation over time is inevitable in a game like this.  Every time a mob dies, new money is "created" out of thin air.  Further, there's nothing wrong with farming in and of itself.  To some people, amassing wealth is the only goal left to attain in this game, for some it's the only "kick" they still get out of it, even if they're <i>not</i> selling the proceeds.<br /><br />The blame here lies squarely with SOE, for 3 reasons:<br /><br />1. Given that inflation is naturally inevitable in a game where money is constantly coming into existance, they should have put in counter-measures (plat sinks) LONG AGO, like the casino, something I've rallied for for years.  Not only did they NOT do this when they should have, once they finally got around to doing it, they fucking took it down after a day or two.  A casino is the perfect plat-sink, and it should be permanent.  <br /><br />2. But letting the natural inflation go unchecked wasn't good enough for these morons.  They had to let these plat-duping bugs remain in-game for months upon months, bringing more plat into the game than probably would have shown up for God knows how long.  They ridiculously cared more about XP exploits.  Wonder how much faster that lvl 10 with 2million plat to blow on equipment is going to level even without exploits or power-leveling?  Fucking gimp retards.  <br /><br />3.  Like drugs in the real world, or alcohol during prohibition, they <i>created</i> the black market that made Yanti what he is.  This is inevitable when you "outlaw" something that you know damn good and well people are going to buy anyway.  They could have prevented this problem <i>and</i> made themselves buttloads of "tax" money in the process.<br /><br />Inexcusable idiocy (and perhaps even complicity in the case of some people) on the part of Sony is the cause of all these woes, in my very sincere opinion.<br /><br /><br /><br />  <br /><br /></span id="msg"></font></td>
